Wash and dry all produce. Halve and peel @shallot{1}. Thinly slice one half; mince other half. Halve and pit @peach{1}, then cut into ½-inch wedges. Strip @thyme{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; discard stems. Roughly chop leaves.

In a #large bowl{}, whisk together ½ tsp @honey{1%tsp}, 1 TBSP @balsamic vinegar{3%tsp}, and a large drizzle of @olive oil{} (we sent more honey and vinegar). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{4%tsp} in a #small pot{} over medium heat. Add minced shallot. Cook, tossing, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add 1 cup water and a large pinch of salt. Bring to a boil, then add @couscous{1/2%cup}. Cover and remove from heat. Let stand until rest of meal is ready.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season @pork chops{12%ounce} all over with salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-4%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and set aside to rest ~{5%minutes}, then thinly slice.

Add sliced shallot and thyme to same pan over medium heat. Cook, tossing, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. (TIP: Add a drizzle of olive oil if pan seems dry.) Stir in @veggie stock concentrate{1}, ½ tsp honey, and ½ cup water (you'll have some honey left over). Scrape up any browned bits on bottom of pan. Simmer until saucy and somewhat reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Add @arugula{2%ounce} and peach to bowl with vinaigrette. Toss to combine. Season with salt and pepper. Fluff couscous with a #fork{}. Season with salt and pepper. Divide couscous and pork between plates. Drizzle with pan sauce. Serve with salad on the side.

> How do you shake up dinnertime? Eat a peach! The stone fruit brings an unexpected but
> utterly delicious twist to the green salad in this recipe. That sweetness also gets
> echoed in the honey herb sauce that's drizzled over the centerpiece: juicy, pan-seared
> pork chops. It's all served next to a bed of couscous, which makes this dish feel as
> hearty and satisfying as it does light and summery.